Note:
FUTURE<T> / PROMISE<T> - Asynchronously computed values.

Promise is the write side; Future is the read side. They share an
underlying shared state. Multiple Futures may share one shared state via
future_clone.

Shared state layout (72 bytes):
  offset 0:  mutex_ptr         (8 bytes) - protects state
  offset 8:  cv_ptr            (8 bytes) - signaled on completion
  offset 16: ready_flag        (8 bytes) - 0 = pending, 1 = ready
  offset 24: value_ptr         (8 bytes) - completed value
  offset 32: error_code        (8 bytes) - 0 if success, otherwise error
  offset 40: error_msg_ptr     (8 bytes) - optional error message (string ptr)
  offset 48: callback_head     (8 bytes) - head of registered callbacks
  offset 56: refcount          (8 bytes) - shared between future + promise + clones
  offset 64: cancelled         (8 bytes) - 1 if cancelled

Callback list node (24 bytes):
  offset 0:  function_ptr      (8 bytes) - callback function
  offset 8:  user_data_ptr     (8 bytes) - user data passed to callback
  offset 16: next_ptr          (8 bytes) - next node

Promise<T> handle (16 bytes):
  offset 0: shared_state_ptr
  offset 8: filled_flag

Future<T> handle (16 bytes):
  offset 0: shared_state_ptr
  offset 8: retrieved_flag

Dependencies:
- threading/sync_core.runa
- core/atomic_core.runa
- memory/layout.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/sync_core.runa" as Sync
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/atomic_core.runa" as Atomic
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Mem

Note: Shared state layout
Constant FP_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant FP_OFF_CV as Integer is 8
Constant FP_OFF_READY as Integer is 16
Constant FP_OFF_VALUE as Integer is 24
Constant FP_OFF_ERROR as Integer is 32
Constant FP_OFF_ERROR_MSG as Integer is 40
Constant FP_OFF_CB_HEAD as Integer is 48
Constant FP_OFF_REFCOUNT as Integer is 56
Constant FP_OFF_CANCELLED as Integer is 64
Constant FP_STATE_SIZE as Integer is 72

Constant FP_CB_FN as Integer is 0
Constant FP_CB_DATA as Integer is 8
Constant FP_CB_NEXT as Integer is 16
Constant FP_CB_SIZE as Integer is 24

Note: Promise / Future handle layout
Constant FP_HANDLE_STATE as Integer is 0
Constant FP_HANDLE_FLAG as Integer is 8
Constant FP_HANDLE_SIZE as Integer is 16

Constant FP_OK as Integer is 1
Constant FP_ERR_INVALID as Integer is 0
Constant FP_ERR_ALREADY_SET as Integer is -1
Constant FP_ERR_NOT_READY as Integer is -2
Constant FP_ERR_CANCELLED as Integer is -3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Shared state lifecycle
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocate and initialize the shared state used by a Promise/Future pair.
Reference-counted so multiple readers and one writer share ownership.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate 72 bytes, create mutex and condvar, initialize all fields to
zero / sane defaults, set refcount to 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One alloc + one mutex create + one condvar create.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The state is heap-owned. Use fp_state_retain / fp_state_release to share
ownership.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "fp_state_create" returns Integer:
    Let s be proc allocate from Memory with FP_STATE_SIZE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc mutex_create from Sync
    If mutex_ptr is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with s
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cv_ptr be proc condvar_create from Sync
    If cv_ptr is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mutex_ptr
        proc deallocate from Memory with s
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX, mutex_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CV, cv_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_VALUE, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR_MSG, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CB_HEAD, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_REFCOUNT, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CANCELLED, 0
    Return s
End Process

Process called "fp_state_retain" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let refcount_ptr be s plus FP_OFF_REFCOUNT
    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with refcount_ptr, 1
    Return s
End Process

Process called "fp_state_release" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let refcount_ptr be s plus FP_OFF_REFCOUNT
    Let old_ref be proc atomic_fetch_sub from Atomic with refcount_ptr, 1
    If old_ref is greater than 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Last reference - free internal state
    Let cb_node be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CB_HEAD
    While cb_node is not equal to 0:
        Let next be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with cb_node, FP_CB_NEXT
        proc deallocate from Memory with cb_node
        Set cb_node to next
    End While

    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CV
    proc condvar_destroy from Sync with cv_ptr
    proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mutex_ptr
    proc deallocate from Memory with s
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Promise<T>
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Promise<T> is the write side of an async value. Each Promise has exactly
one associated Future (or more via clones). promise_set_value resolves the
future and wakes any waiters.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate the promise handle and a fresh shared state.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One alloc per promise plus the state cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The Promise handle must be destroyed exactly once via promise_destroy.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "promise_create" returns Integer:
    Let s be proc fp_state_create
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let p be proc allocate from Memory with FP_HANDLE_SIZE
    If p is equal to 0:
        proc fp_state_release with s
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with p, FP_HANDLE_STATE, s
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with p, FP_HANDLE_FLAG, 0
    Return p
End Process

Process called "promise_destroy" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with p, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    proc fp_state_release with s
    proc deallocate from Memory with p
    Return FP_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Spawn a paired Future from a Promise. Both share the same shared state via
refcount increment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate a Future handle, set its shared state pointer to the same state as
the Promise, increment the refcount.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One alloc plus one atomic fetch_add.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The Future must be destroyed via future_destroy.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "promise_get_future" takes p as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with p, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let f be proc allocate from Memory with FP_HANDLE_SIZE
    If f is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc fp_state_retain with s
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE, s
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_FLAG, 0
    Return f
End Process

@Reasoning
Helper: fire registered callbacks after a value or error has been set.
Caller must hold the state mutex when calling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walk the callback list, invoking each via its function pointer. The callback
signature is (user_data, value_ptr, error_code).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(n) in callback count. Callbacks are released after invocation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller MUST hold the state mutex.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "fp_fire_callbacks_locked" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cb_node be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CB_HEAD
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_VALUE
    Let error_code be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR
    While cb_node is not equal to 0:
        Let fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with cb_node, FP_CB_FN
        Let user_data be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with cb_node, FP_CB_DATA
        Let next be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with cb_node, FP_CB_NEXT

        Note: Indirect call via runtime callback dispatcher.
        Note: The callback is expected to take (user_data, value_ptr, error_code).
        Note: We use call_indirect_3 from the runtime ABI for portability.
        If fn is not equal to 0:
            proc fp_dispatch_callback with fn, user_data, value_ptr, error_code
        End If

        proc deallocate from Memory with cb_node
        Set cb_node to next
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CB_HEAD, 0
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Internal callback dispatcher. The function-pointer ABI is platform-defined;
this wrapper centralizes the indirection so future tail-call optimization
or context-injection can be added in one place.
@End Implementation

@Implementation
Currently performs the indirect call via the platform's standard calling
convention. Builds atop the function-pointer call primitive emitted by
the codegen when an Integer expression is invoked as a process.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Branch-target indirect call - prefer batching if many callbacks share a
function pointer (deduplicate at registration time, not here).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
fn must be a valid code pointer produced from a registered Process.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "fp_dispatch_callback" takes fn as Integer, user_data as Integer, value_ptr as Integer, error_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Direct indirect call via the language's first-class function pointer mechanism. The callback's signature is: Process takes (user_data, value_ptr, error_code) returns Integer. The runtime indirect-call primitive is delegated through fp_runtime_call_indirect_3.
    If fn is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Compute zero so unused branches don't optimize away the args.
    Let _u be user_data
    Let _v be value_ptr
    Let _e be error_code
    Note: Indirect callback dispatch is provided by the runtime's
    Note: call_indirect_3 primitive registered via the FFI/closure module.
    Note: We delegate via the closure runtime when available; otherwise we
    Note: return 0 to signal that callback delivery requires a runtime that
    Note: links the closure dispatcher.
    Return proc fp_runtime_call_indirect_3 with fn, _u, _v, _e
End Process

@Reasoning
Runtime indirect-call shim. Implemented at the FFI layer; declared here so
the compiler can resolve the symbol and the linker fills it in at link
time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
A weak external symbol resolves to the closure dispatcher in
runtime/integration/ffi. The implementation here exists so the source file
type-checks; the linker replaces this body via runtime override hooks.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One indirect branch.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must guarantee `fn` is a valid 3-arg integer-returning code pointer.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "fp_runtime_call_indirect_3" takes fn as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer, c as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: The runtime FFI closure dispatcher overrides this symbol via the
    Note: link-time weak-binding mechanism documented in
    Note: runtime/integration/ffi/closure_invoke.runa. Until that module
    Note: links, callback invocation is a no-op (returns 0). Tests of
    Note: future_then validate the callback list-registration path; the
    Note: invocation path becomes live once closure_invoke is integrated.
    If fn is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let _a be a
    Let _b be b
    Let _c be c
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Set the future's value. Fires all registered callbacks and wakes any
blocked future_get calls. Returns FP_ERR_ALREADY_SET if the future has
already been resolved.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lock the mutex, check the ready flag, set value + ready flag, broadcast
the condvar, fire callbacks, unlock.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One mutex+broadcast+optional callback walk. Resolve as early as possible
so consumers wake quickly.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Setting value on a destroyed promise is a logic error.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "promise_set_value" takes p as Integer, value_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with p, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    Let already_ready be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY
    If already_ready is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return FP_ERR_ALREADY_SET
    End If

    Let cancelled be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CANCELLED
    If cancelled is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return FP_ERR_CANCELLED
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_VALUE, value_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY, 1

    Let cv_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CV
    proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with cv_ptr

    proc fp_fire_callbacks_locked with s

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with p, FP_HANDLE_FLAG, 1
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return FP_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Set the future to an error state. Same wake/callback semantics as
set_value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lock, set ready and error fields, broadcast, fire callbacks, unlock.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Same as set_value.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
error_msg_ptr may be 0 if no message. Caller retains ownership.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "promise_set_error" takes p as Integer, error_code as Integer, error_msg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If p is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with p, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    Let already_ready be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY
    If already_ready is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return FP_ERR_ALREADY_SET
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_VALUE, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR, error_code
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR_MSG, error_msg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY, 1

    Let cv_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CV
    proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with cv_ptr

    proc fp_fire_callbacks_locked with s

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with p, FP_HANDLE_FLAG, 1
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return FP_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Future<T>
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Create a stand-alone resolved future for cases where the value is already
known. Allocates a state, marks ready, returns a Future handle.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Build a fresh state with ready_flag=1 and value pre-set.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One alloc + sync init; no thread blocking.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Result must be released via future_destroy.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "future_create_ready" takes value_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let s be proc fp_state_create
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_VALUE, value_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY, 1
    Let f be proc allocate from Memory with FP_HANDLE_SIZE
    If f is equal to 0:
        proc fp_state_release with s
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE, s
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_FLAG, 0
    Return f
End Process

Process called "future_destroy" takes f as Integer returns Integer:
    If f is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    proc fp_state_release with s
    proc deallocate from Memory with f
    Return FP_OK
End Process

Process called "future_clone" takes f as Integer returns Integer:
    If f is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let nf be proc allocate from Memory with FP_HANDLE_SIZE
    If nf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc fp_state_retain with s
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with nf, FP_HANDLE_STATE, s
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with nf, FP_HANDLE_FLAG, 0
    Return nf
End Process

@Reasoning
Block until the future is ready, then return the resolved value pointer.
If the future errored, returns 0; caller can check future_get_error.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lock the state mutex, loop on ready flag, wait on the condvar. Once ready,
read the value pointer (or 0 if errored), unlock, return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot path: if already ready, one mutex acquire + read. Otherwise condvar
wait.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returned pointer's lifetime is governed by the promise-side resolver.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "future_get" takes f as Integer returns Integer:
    If f is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX
    Let cv_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CV
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    Let waiting be 1
    While waiting is equal to 1:
        Let ready be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY
        If ready is not equal to 0:
            Set waiting to 0
        Otherwise:
            proc condvar_wait from Sync with cv_ptr, mutex_ptr
        End If
    End While

    Let err be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR
    Let value_ptr be 0
    If err is equal to 0:
        Set value_ptr to proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_VALUE
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_FLAG, 1
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return value_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning
Non-blocking check: returns 1 if the future has resolved, 0 otherwise.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read the ready flag under the lock.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One mutex acquire.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Safe.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "future_is_ready" takes f as Integer returns Integer:
    If f is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Let ready be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return ready
End Process

@Reasoning
Retrieve the error code from a resolved future. Returns 0 if no error or
the future is still pending.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read FP_OFF_ERROR under the lock.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One mutex acquire.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Safe.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "future_get_error" takes f as Integer returns Integer:
    If f is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr
