@Reasoning
Register a callback to be invoked when the future resolves. If already
resolved, fires the callback immediately under the lock.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lock the state mutex. If ready, dispatch immediately. Otherwise, allocate a
callback node and prepend to the callback list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Either fires immediately (O(1)) or registers (O(1) prepend).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Callback fn must remain valid until the future resolves.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "future_then" takes f as Integer, callback_fn as Integer, user_data as Integer returns Integer:
    If f is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    Let ready be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY
    If ready is not equal to 0:
        Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_VALUE
        Let error_code be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR
        proc fp_dispatch_callback with callback_fn, user_data, value_ptr, error_code
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return FP_OK
    End If

    Let node be proc allocate from Memory with FP_CB_SIZE
    If node is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with node, FP_CB_FN, callback_fn
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with node, FP_CB_DATA, user_data
    Let old_head be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CB_HEAD
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with node, FP_CB_NEXT, old_head
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CB_HEAD, node

    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return FP_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Cancel a pending future. Wakes any waiters with an error; if the future is
already ready, cancel is a no-op.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Lock, set cancelled flag and error code, broadcast condvar.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One mutex + broadcast.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Safe.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "future_cancel" takes f as Integer returns Integer:
    If f is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with f, FP_HANDLE_STATE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Let ready be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY
    If ready is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return FP_ERR_ALREADY_SET
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CANCELLED, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_ERROR, FP_ERR_CANCELLED
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_READY, 1
    Let cv_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with s, FP_OFF_CV
    proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with cv_ptr
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return FP_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Combinators
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
future_all waits for all futures in the array to resolve, then returns
FP_OK. Errors are recorded in the output array of resolved values; caller
inspects each individually. Polling-based for simplicity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Array of futures + count. Iterate calling future_get on each in turn -
since future_get blocks, the call sequence is equivalent to wait-all even
though concurrent resolution is supported.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Total wait time is bounded by the slowest future. No spinning - each
future_get blocks until its target resolves.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
out_values_array must have capacity for count*8 bytes.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "future_all" takes futures_array as Integer, count as Integer, out_values_array as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Resolve every future in the array.  If any rejects with an error
    Note: code, return that code immediately (Promise.all semantics).  All
    Note: remaining futures still get future_get called on them so that the
    Note: caller's out_values_array is fully populated and so that the
    Note: rejection of one future does not strand other promise consumers.
    If futures_array is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If count is less than or equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let aggregate_error be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let f be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with futures_array, offset
        Let v be proc future_get with f
        If out_values_array is not equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_values_array, offset, v
        End If
        If aggregate_error is equal to 0:
            Let e be proc future_get_error with f
            If e is not equal to 0:
                Set aggregate_error to e
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If aggregate_error is not equal to 0:
        Return aggregate_error
    End If
    Return FP_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
future_any returns as soon as the first future resolves. The index of the
first resolved future is written to out_index. The other futures are not
cancelled (caller may choose to cancel them).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Poll each future_is_ready in order; if any is ready, return its index.
Otherwise yield the thread (cooperative wait) and retry.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Busy-poll-with-yield. For latency-critical paths the caller can switch to
manual condvar-based fan-in by sharing a single signal future.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
out_index_holder must point to writable 8-byte storage.
@End Security_Scope

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/threading.runa" as Threading

Process called "future_any" takes futures_array as Integer, count as Integer, out_index_holder as Integer, out_value_holder as Integer returns Integer:
    If futures_array is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If count is less than or equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If out_index_holder is equal to 0:
        Return FP_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Let polling be 1
    While polling is equal to 1:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let offset be i multiplied by 8
            Let f be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with futures_array, offset
            If f is not equal to 0:
                Let ready be proc future_is_ready with f
                If ready is not equal to 0:
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_index_holder, 0, i
                    If out_value_holder is not equal to 0:
                        Let v be proc future_get with f
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_value_holder, 0, v
                    End If
                    Return FP_OK
                End If
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc platform_thread_yield from Threading
    End While
    Return FP_ERR_INVALID
End Process
